04862nam a22005175i 9780813539270DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20062006nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135392707 a10.36019/97808135392702doi  a(DE-B1597)530240  a(OCoLC)71842945  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aSOC0000002bisacsh1 aLeibing, Annette, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aThinking About Dementia :bCulture, Loss, and the Anthropology of Senility /cAnnette Leibing, Lawrence Cohen. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b1  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Medical Anthropology00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tIntroduction: Thinking about Dementia -- t1. Dementia-Near-Death and "Life Itself" -- t2. The Borderlands of Primary Care: Physician and Family Perspectives on "Troublesome" Behaviors of People with Dementia -- t3. Negotiating the Moral Status of Trouble: The Experiences of Forgetful Individuals Diagnosed with No Dementia -- t4. Diagnosing Dementia: Epidemiological and Clinical Data as Cultural Text -- t5. The Biomedical Deconstruction of Senility and the Persistent Stigmatization of Old Age in the United States -- t6. Genetic Susceptibility and Alzheimer's Disease: The Penetrance and Uptake of Genetic Knowledge -- t7. Coherence without Facticity in Dementia: The Case of Mrs. Fine -- t8. Creative Storytelling and Self-Expression among People with Dementia -- t9. Embodied Selfhood: An Ethnographic Exploration of Alzheimer's Disease -- t10. Normality and Difference: Institutional Classification and the Constitution of Subjectivity in a Dutch Nursing Home -- t11. Divided Gazes: Alzheimer's Disease, the Person within, and Death in Life -- t12 Being a Good Rōjin: Senility, Power, and Self-Actualization in Japan -- tCONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aBringing together essays by nineteen respected scholars, this volume approaches dementia from a variety of angles, exploring its historical, psychological, and philosophical implications. The authors employ a cross-cultural perspective that is based on ethnographic fieldwork and focuses on questions of age, mind, voice, self, loss, temporality, memory, and affect. Taken together, the essays make four important and interrelated contributions to our understanding of the mental status of the elderly. First, cross-cultural data show that the aging process, while biologically influenced, is also culturally constructed. Second, ethnographic reports raise questions about the diagnostic criteria used for defining the elderly as demented. Third, case studies show how a diagnosis affects a patient's treatment in both clinical and familial settings. Finally, the collection highlights the gap that separates current biological understandings of aging from its cultural meanings. As Alzheimer's disease and other forms of dementia continue to command an ever-increasing amount of attention in medicine and psychology, this book will be essential reading for anthropologists, social scientists, and health care professionals.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access. Unless otherwise specified in the content, the work is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-NoDerivatives (CC BY-NC-ND) license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/3.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aCohen, Lawrence, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP